    if cleaned_df.tweet[i] in unique_tweets:
        
        duplicate_tweets.append(cleaned_df.tweet[i])

pattern2 = "^retweet @[a-zA-Z0-9_]+:"

From the code below,the 'averaged_perceptron_tagger' model is a machine learning model that is trained on a large corpus of text to assign POS tags to words in a sentence. This model is widely used for natural language processing tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, and information retrieval.

After downloading the required NLTK datasets,I applyied the 'tweet_cleaner' function to each tweet in the 'tokenizer_tweets' column of the 'cleaned_df' DataFrame, and storing the cleaned tweets in a new column called 'cleaned_tweets'.

In [94]:
import nltk
nltk.download('stopwords')
# Defining Stopwords 
STOPWORDS = stopwords.words('english')

def tweet_cleaner(tweet_tokens):

    cleaned_tokens = []

    for token, tag in pos_tag(tweet_tokens):
        
        #Removing links
        token = re.sub('http[s]?://(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-_@.&+#]|[!*\(\),]|'\
                       '(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+','', token)
        
        #Removing mentions
        token = re.sub("(@[A-Za-z0-9_]+)","", token)

        # Checking for POS label and converting it for Lemmatizer input
        if tag.startswith("NN"):
            pos = 'n'
        elif tag.startswith('VB'):
            pos = 'v'
        else:
            pos = 'a'
            
        #Init Lemmatizer   
        tweet_lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
        cleaned_token = tweet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(token, pos)
        
        #Checking for punctuation, word lenght less than 2 then removing stopwords 
        if cleaned_token not in string.punctuation and len(cleaned_token) > 2 and cleaned_token not in STOPWORDS:
            cleaned_tokens.append(cleaned_token)
            
    return cleaned_tokens

The code below imports Tokenizer and pad_sequences classes from the keras.preprocessing.text module It initializes the input_length and vocab_length variables. Then, it creates an instance of Tokenizer with the following parameters: filters: it specifies which characters to remove from the text. In this case, we want to keep all characters, so we set it to an empty string. lower: it specifies whether to convert the text to lowercase or not. In this case, we want to keep the original case, so we set it to False. oov_token: it specifies the token to use for out-of-vocabulary words. In this case, we set it to "". It fits the tokenizer on the training data (X_train) and sets the num_words parameter to vocab_length. Finally, it pads the sequences of the training and test data using pad_sequences method to the maximum length of input_length.

In [102]:
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer 
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences 
t = time.process_time()

input_length = 60
vocab_length = 60000

tokenizer = Tokenizer(filters="", lower=False, oov_token="<oov>")
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(X)
tokenizer.num_words = vocab_length

X_train = pad_sequences(tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_train), maxlen=input_length)
X_test  = pad_sequences(tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_test) , maxlen=input_length)

print(f'Padding Dataset Finished !')
print(f'CPU Time Taken: {round(time.process_time()-t)} seconds')

From the code below,the embedding matrix has a shape of (60000, 100), meaning that it contains word embeddings for 60000 unique words, where each word embedding has a dimension of 100. The embedding matrix is initialized with zeros, and for each word in the tokenizer's word index that exists in the Word2Vec model's vocabulary, the corresponding row in the embedding matrix is updated with the Word2Vec embedding vector for that word.

embedding_matrix = np.zeros((vocab_length, size))

for word, token in tokenizer.word_index.items():
    if word2vec_model.wv.__contains__(word):
        embedding_matrix[token] = word2vec_model.wv.__getitem__(word)


print("Embedding Matrix Shape:", embedding_matrix.shape)

In [104]:
from keras.layers import Embedding
embedding_layer = Embedding(input_dim = vocab_length,
                                output_dim = size,
                                weights=[embedding_matrix],
                                input_length=input_length,
                                trainable=False)

The code below defines a Bidirectional LSTM model using the Keras API. It is a type of Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) model architecture that consists of an embedding layer, two Bidirectional LSTM layers with 128 units each, and a Dense layer with a sigmoid activation function that outputs a single value. LSTMs are capable of learning long-term dependencies in sequential data and are widely used in various natural language processing (NLP) tasks, such as language modeling and sentiment analysis.

The input shape to the model is (batch_size, input_length), where batch_size is the number of samples in each batch and input_length is the length of each input sequence (in this case, 60).

The output shape of the model is (batch_size, 1), which corresponds to a single binary classification output.

In [105]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Bidirectional
from keras.layers import LSTM
def BiLSTM_Model():
    model = Sequential([
        embedding_layer,
        Bidirectional(LSTM(units=128, return_sequences=True)),
        Bidirectional(LSTM(units=128, return_sequences=False)),
        Dense(units=1, activation='sigmoid')
    ],
    name='BiLSTM_Model')
    return model

From the code below,the compile method is being called on a cnn_model object, which should have already been defined earlier in the code.

The loss parameter is set to 'binary_crossentropy', which is a commonly used loss function for binary classification problems. The goal of this function is to measure the difference between the true labels and the predicted labels of the model.

The optimizer parameter is set to an instance of the Adam optimizer, which is a commonly used optimization algorithm for deep learning models. The lr parameter of the Adam optimizer is set to 0.001, which controls the learning rate of the optimizer.

#Visualizing the performance of the first model
def plot_acc_loss(history):

    acc = history.history['accuracy'] # extracts the accuracy values from the history
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy'] #retrieves the validation accuracy values from the history
    loss = history.history['loss']  # retrieves the training loss values from the history
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']   #retrieves the validation loss values from the history
    epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)  #extracting the training metrics for each epoch

    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label = 'Training Accuracy') #plotting the training accuracy over the epochs with blue dots
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'r', label = 'Validation Accuracy') #plotting validation accuracy shown in a red line.
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy') #used to set the title of the plot.
    plt.xlabel('Epochs') #setting the label for the x-axis 
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy') #setting the label for the y-axis
    plt.legend() #identifying which line corresponds to which dataset

    plt.figure()  #creating a  figure, 
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label = 'Training Loss') #plotting the loss over the epochs with blue dots
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'r', label = 'Validation Loss') #plotting validation loss shown in a red line.
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss') #used to set the title of the plot.
    plt.xlabel('Epochs') #setting the label for the x-axis
    plt.ylabel('Loss') #setting the label for the y-axis
    plt.legend() #identifying which line corresponds to which dataset
    plt.show() #showing the figure

In [52]:
#Visualizing the second model
def plot_acc_loss(history):

    acc = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label = 'Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'r', label = 'Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label = 'Training Loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'r', label = 'Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

The results above indicate that KNN(claasifier2) has the highest accuracy score with 0.54, followed by Naive Bayes classifier(classifier3) with the same accuracy score of 0.54, and then Random Forest classifier with a lower accuracy score of 0.52(classifier1). This means that classifier 2 and 3 are better at predicting the sentiment of the tweets in the test dataset compared to classifier 1.
